\subsection*{How prevalent are internal constraints across species and populations?}

% Predicting changes in growth in response to longer seasons requires understanding how much variation is possible inter-annually, within individuals. 
New evidence suggests inter-annual variation growth may be limited because of internal constraints that prevent plants from fully using longer seasons CITES. If true, this would have major ramifications for how much we expect tree growth to shift with warming and fundamental plant biology, but requires much more study. Certainly, all plants are limited by internal constraints and how quickly they can build new tissues but selection towards different growth strategies (e.g., acquisitive versus conservative) should drive variation in these constraints across species, and possibly populations. As budset---which indicates the end of height growth---is strongly locally adapted CITES, we should expect variation in these constraints across population, as selection should favor individuals better matches to local environmental optima CITES. 

Current results generally scmear across species and populations (e.g., using NDVI CITES), but new studies could rapidly test for constraints across species and populations, to work towards a predictive framework using phylogeny and traits to predict these constraints. %For example, latitudinal or elevational studies can also model effects due to the local site, which may correlate with population-level constraints.  
Studies across space could provide early inferences by studying how growing seasons measured by vegetative versus wood phenology vary---and attributing variation through models that nest species within populations and include traits, while experiments could provide more robust tests. While juvenile stages of trees are often more flexible than their adult forms, they still often provide predictable inference in differences across species and populations, and so should be integrated far more into studies of how season length affects growth. Using saplings and controlled environments could quickly test how much growth can shift with longer season---providing a potentially standardized way to compare constraints across species and populations. Such studies could also begin to tease out effects of increased growth rates due to warmer temperatures versus longer seasons. 

