\subsection*{How do external drivers and internal constraints act together?}

Most research on how growth impacts growing season length with climate change has been focused on this question, with certain studies documenting potential constraints and others focused on teasing out how temperature, drought and other external forces impact growth, but fundamentally they are interconnected and thus any useful model must include these drivers together.  We argue addressing the pattern across space---and benchmarking inter-annual responses within that pattern---alongside documenting the scale of internal constraints across species and populations will be critical to then build up to compare responses of external and internal drivers. As these new data come together with trait-mediated ecophylogenetic models, we expect real advances will require large-scale experiments.  

The complexity of climate change and plant growth in response to longer, warmer seasons makes experiments vital to building useful mechanistic models for forecasting. Observational data---used mainly to date to tackle this question (CITEFIG?)---generally confounds multiple external drivers, including season length, temperature and precipitation regimes CITES, making it impossible to tease out actual drivers in most data. In particular, mechanistic models will need to tease out changes in season length from warming that affects rates; a challenge best addressed by experiments. While experimenting on trees is difficult, previous challenges in climate change research have used it under similar tricky problems (CITES) we expect similar experiments will be critical here. Small-scale experiments on juveniles, however, can help inform the underlying model, select representative species to focus on and help develop predictions for large-scale findings. 


\emph{Conclusions:} 
Anthropogenic climate change has often been described as an unfortunate and unplanned experiment. Like many experiments, it has highlighted important biology we do not know well, requiring us to rediscover dusty old fundamentals, and also expose their limits. Understanding when, how and why longer seasons lead to increased tree growth requires an interdisciplinary reckoning with how temperature, time and a suite of external and internal drivers affect plant growth. A mechanistic understanding of how these drivers integrate to affect growth will be critical for accurate models of future forest and related carbon dynamics, with implications for projections of carbon sequestration and carbon markets. 

